<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 7:11<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2774a4c0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>7.</label.designator><headtext>Lay and Expert Opinion Testimony</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71fa1f6682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>7:11.</label.designator><headtext>Subjects of expert testimony—Sanity</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Mental sanity is a factual matter based on personal observation of the subject or on fact-based hypothetical questions posed to an expert witness. <eos/><bos/>Often, the question arises concerning the past sanity of an individual such as a testator at the time of his will execution or a criminal defendant at the time of the crime. <eos/><bos/>An individual&apos;s present sanity may be an issue in a competency hearing regarding a criminal defendant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I78abade074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Witness statements that a person was in a good humor, looked mad, or similar descriptions of emotion are facts and not conclusions or opinions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I78abade174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference><?page no="196"?>] Also, the court has held that a statement by a witness who has observed the subject for a long time that the subject always acted sane and that he observed nothing to indicate insanity would support an opinion that the individual was sane,[<footnote.reference refid="I78abade274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] but would not be enough to support an opinion of insanity. <eos/><bos/>However, a subscribing witness to a will may state his opinion as to the sanity of the testator without giving any facts to support his opinion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I78abade374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Two opinions from the 1800&apos;s by Justice Lumpkin largely fixed the Georgia rules in regard to expert testimony on sanity: <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1849001465" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Idb923dd174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Potts v. House</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78abd4f074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] considered testamentary capacity and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1860002856" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Idb93012174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Choice v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78abd4f174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] considered criminal responsibility. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1849001465" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Idb93c47174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Potts</ital></cite.query>, the Georgia Supreme Court held that lay witness opinions on sanity were admissible, but must be <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“accompanied with the facts on which they are founded.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I78abd4f274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1950104765" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb9487c274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Brock v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I78abfc0074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court held that the trial judge should inquire into the opportunity of the witness for observation of the individual in question and permit the witness to state his opinion, if he has had adequate opportunity for observation. <eos/><bos/>Then, the jury decides if the facts justify the witness&apos; opinion.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia Court of Appeals held that a psychologist was properly qualified as a sanity expert.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I78abfc0174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] The court followed substantial precedent in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1966112846" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb95c04274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Moore v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78abfc0274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] to hold that an expert witness&apos; sanity opinion must be based on his own observation of facts personally known to him or on evidence supported hypothetical questions.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In a case of first impression, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1972129074" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb96aaa274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Petty v. Folsom,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78abfc0374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court considered whether a psychiatrist&apos;s expert opinion as to mental condition could be based upon statements made to him by the patient (hearsay).<eos/><bos/> The Court stated:</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/><?page no="197"?>In our opinion whether an examining physician is or is not a psychiatrist is a matter which may affect the extent of his expertise in evaluating mental condition, and therefore may affect the weight of any opinion or evaluation, a matter to be determined by a jury, but it does not affect admissibility, nor is admissibility precluded by the fact that his opinions and evaluations are based on conversations with the patient. <eos/><bos/>Under the circumstances here disclosed the trial judge erred in excluding and restricting the testimony of the physician concerning his opinions and diagnoses of the mental condition of the plaintiff.<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I78abfc0474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>]</paratext></para></display.quote><paratext>Thus, an expert may base his opinion as to mental condition on statements made to him by the patient.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1978109888" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb98314274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Redfield v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78ac231074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] the court held that an expert opinion as to mental condition may be based, in part, on hearsay.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1977135839" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb991ba274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Redwing Carriers, Inc. v. Knight</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78ac231174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>] recognized that market value and mental condition are exceptions to the rule that an expert may not base his opinion on hearsay. <eos/><bos/>Jurors are not bound by the opinions of expert witnesses regarding sanity; instead they may rely on the rebuttable presumption of sanity, unless the proof is overwhelming.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I78ac231274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">15</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I78abade074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-7-704" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Idb8fccd074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-7-704(b)</cite.query>, providing that an expert in a criminal proceeding may not testify as to whether the accused had the mental state necessary for conviction of the charged offense (an exception to the “ultimate issue” rule).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abade174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1955105494" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb90420274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Rooker v. State, 211 Ga. 361, 86 S.E.2d 307 (1955)</cite.query><?page no="196"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abade274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1889062195" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Idb90b73274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Taylor v. State, 83 Ga. 647, 10 S.E. 442 (1889)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1906011445" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Idb90b73574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Proctor v. Pointer, 127 Ga. 134, 56 S.E. 111 (1906)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1926105782" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Idb90b73874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Mars v. State, 163 Ga. 43, 135 S.E. 410 (1926)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1932105790" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Idb90b73b74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">McWilliam v. Pattillo, 173 Ga. 771, 161 S.E. 597 (1931)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abade374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1849001465" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Idb91537174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Potts v. House, 6 Ga. 324, 1849 WL 1583 (1849)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1949105090" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb91537574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Whitfield v. Pitts, 205 Ga. 259, 53 S.E.2d 549 (1949)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1955105525" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb91537874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Tinnerman v. Baldwin, 211 Ga. 532, 87 S.E.2d 65 (1955)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1983145971" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb91537b74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">In re Estate of Harris, 251 Ga. 535, 307 S.E.2d 482 (1983)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1920031315" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000104" ID="Idb91537d74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">93 A. L. R. 1049</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1968011273" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000108" ID="Idb91537f74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">17 A. L. R. 3d 503</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abd4f074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1849001465" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Idb928bf174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Potts v. House, 6 Ga. 324, 1849 WL 1583 (1849)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abd4f174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1860002856" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Idb93283174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Choice v. State, 31 Ga. 424, 1860 WL 2408 (1860)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abd4f274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1849001465" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Idb93eb8174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Potts v. House, 6 Ga. 324, 1849 WL 1583 (1849)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abfc0074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1950104765" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb94aed274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Brock v. State, 206 Ga. 397, 57 S.E.2d 279 (1950)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abfc0174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1986138259" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb954b1274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Cannon v. State, 179 Ga. App. 142, 345 S.E.2d 623 (1986)</cite.query>, the court appointed a psychologist who testified as to sanity as a witness for the court.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abfc0274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1966112846" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb960e6274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Moore v. State, 221 Ga. 636, 146 S.E.2d 895 (1966)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abfc0374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1972129074" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb96d1b274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Petty v. Folsom, 229 Ga. 477, 192 S.E.2d 246 (1972)</cite.query><?page no="197"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78abfc0474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1972129074" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb97950274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">229 Ga. 477, 480, 481, 192 S. E. 2d 246 (1972)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78ac231074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1978109888" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb987f6274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Redfield v. State, 240 Ga. 460, 241 S.E.2d 217 (1978)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78ac231174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="1977135839" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb9942b274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Redwing Carriers, Inc. v. Knight, 143 Ga. App. 668, 239 S.E.2d 686 (1977)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="2003637872" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb9942b574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Roebuck v. State, 277 Ga. 200, 586 S.E.2d 651 (2003)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I78ac231274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017118" w-serial-number="2030239081" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idb99b7e274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Simon v. State, 321 Ga. App. 1, 740 S.E.2d 819 (2013)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 7:11<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
